I was two years old the first time that I rode to the herd and then I spent the next 17 years doing it as often as possible. After I turned 19 and was in college, I didn’t have as much time to show and I was a burn out from spending so many years riding every single day, whether I wanted to or not. This stud was a huge part of my career and I am so thankful that I ever had the opportunity to swing a leg over him. I can still remember the day that we picked him up in Waurika Oklahoma and I was so excited! I rounded the corner of the barn, and here was this horse walking on his back feet looking over the stalls…I meekly grabbed his halter and went in and caught him. I never had a stud that I had to lead on a stud chain before so I was timidly waiting for him to act up. He never did. It took about a week of me pestering him spending every moment I could with him before he became my horse. He would come to me if he was turned out he rested his head on my shoulder. I could ride him in a halter and his winter blanket right next to a mare, and he wouldn’t make a peep. We became best friends. He was the keeper of my secrets as a young adolescent. There are not enough thank youse in the world that I can say to Randy and Sue Magers for letting me have him and treat him as my own for so many years getting these old videos and DVDs of runs has been so fun I can’t wait to share more but this one run was so special to me. I had only had him a few months at this point. I really wasn’t sure exactly how to ride him still, this run we started putting it all together. I’m thankful to have rode his babies and to know that it wasn’t just a one time deal with him. His genetics are so incredible and he throws some of the most calm and sound minded babies. Here’s just a small peek at who I used to be. Thanks for a lot of fun rides Fatboy.

32 trips around the sun ☀️ And I definitely don’t know everything but I would love to share a few things I have learned. So here’s 32 tips on my 32nd birthday 🤩

1. God is real. Heaven is real.
2. People make time for the people they want to make time for. 
3. Life is short. Live each day with purpose. .
4. You don’t have to get along with everyone. It’s ok to have boundaries for people. 
5. Regret is the worst. 
6. Saying no to things is just as important, if not more important than saying yes. 
7. You are not your thoughts.
8. Positivity is a choice. Make it daily.
9. “Life doesn’t happen to you, it happens for you.”
10. You just can’t please everyone.
11. People really like to give their unsolicited advice.
12. Dress up if you want. Or not. As long as you feel good that’s what matters! 
13. Gossip is for the birds. 
14. Pick your friends wisely.
15. Don’t get caught up worrying what other people think.
16. Support other women.
17. You are stronger than you think. 
18. Take care of your skin!
19. Rules are meant to be broken.
20. Confidence is key. 
21. Dress for your body. 
22. Grief sucks and everyone handles it differently.
23. There are 7 days in a week and someday isn’t one of them.
24. Only compete with yourself.
25. Love your body. 
26. Hurt people hurt people.
27. The right lipstick can make all the difference. 
28. Being nice is cool. 
29. Everyone has a love language, know yours.
30. Make lists and set goals. 
31. Working out is about way more than a number on a scale.
32. The key to having it all is knowing that you already do.

Watching the Jr Youth Scholarship from my computer has me feeling very nostalgic. 

One of the most cherished memories of my childhood was showing at the scholarship cutting. Getting to be surrounded by friends and the thrill of the competition was palpable.

The sights and sounds of those days are etched in my memory forever. The smell of a sweaty horse after showing, the sizzle of water hitting the pavement as we led our horses back, and the cheers from the crowd urging us on - it created an atmosphere of electric excitement.

But the true treasure of those days was the camaraderie we shared. Spending countless hours together, preparing our horses and supporting each other in the arena, we formed unbreakable bonds that have lasted a lifetime. Those were the friends who truly understood the love and dedication we had for our horses.

Cutting taught me valuable life lessons. Responsibility, sportsmanship, and the significance of teamwork.

Riding to the herd was a moment of pure exhilaration. I felt like I was on top of the world, knowing how hard I had worked to get ready for that very moment. Now, as I look back and watch the kids of today compete, I see that same nerve-wracking excitement in their eyes. It warms my heart to know that they're experiencing the same emotions I once felt.

If I could go back in time, I would tell my younger self to relish every moment - the hard work, the victories, and the fun with friends. Those days were about more than just winning; they were about forging memories that would stay with me forever.

Seeing them ride to the herd, fully immersed in the sport that once consumed my life, fills me with joy. The passion for horses and the sport still burns within me, even though I no longer compete.

Looking back, I am grateful for the memories and life lessons that cutting horses brought into my life. They've shaped the person I am today.

Today we celebrated my Granny and the amazing 98 years that she lived. It’s impossible for me to fathom how much the world has changed since 1925. 

I spent the majority of my childhood living next door and running across the patch to spend time with her. 

When we went through her closet we picked pieces that she handmade for herself to wear. Our dresses are over 50 years old and still in perfect condition. 

She has made me a lot of clothes over the years but this dress today was the most special item I’ve ever worn of hers. 

I’m selfishly so sad that she’s gone because one more day would be so perfect but I’m so blessed that I got to have my Granny for 32 years. 

In her special way to end a call or conversation. I love you good, bye. 

I can’t wait to see you again.

This week we lost Cunu, he has left an emptiness that's hard to put into words. He wasn't just a horse; he was a cherished member of our family who brought us immeasurable joy and shared in the highs and lows of life.

Cunu's story intertwined with Cody's in the most remarkable way. They started their adventure together when Cody was just 13 and Cunu was a spirited 6-year-old. From the rodeo wins to a college national title and multiple circuit finals wins, their accomplishments were the stuff of legends. But it wasn't just the victories that made their journey special; it was the bond they shared.

For 23 incredible years, they were a duo like no other. Through heartaches and celebrations, Cunu was a constant presence, a silent listener to all of life's stories. And over the last 8 years, I had the privilege of riding him too, watching our nieces and nephews giggle as they experienced the magic of being on his back, and capturing countless moments in photos that will forever remind us of his gentle spirit.

Cunu wasn't just Cody's partner; he became everyone's friend. His calm demeanor, wise eyes, and the way he nuzzled into our lives made him an irreplaceable companion. Every time we look at those photos, it's like he's still with us, reminding us to cherish every moment.

As we say goodbye to Cunu, the ache in our hearts is profound. But we're also filled with gratitude for the years of love, laughter, and memories he gifted us. He might have left this physical world, but his spirit will forever trot through our thoughts, reminding us of the beautiful journey we shared.

social_posts.post_text: It’s back number night!!!

In the heart of Las Vegas, a city known for its vibrant spirit, we experienced a stark reminder of life’s fragility. Just 45 minutes after leaving the Thomas & Mack Center, tragedy struck, leaving us heartbroken for the lives lost and the families forever changed. This moment is a somber reflection on the unpredictability of life.

However, in the midst of darkness, the resilient spirit of Vegas shines through. We stand together, Vegas strong, in the face of adversity, supporting each other and finding strength in unity.

As I share the outfits I wore yesterday, it’s with a heavy heart but also with a resolve to appreciate every moment we have. Let’s cherish our loved ones and hold onto the joy they bring into our lives. #VegasStrong #CherishEveryMoment
